                                <p><hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 60.&#8212;<hi rend="italic"
                                                >Light febrile attack following intermittent fever,
                                                but not influenced specially by the action of the
                                                malarial poison; debility; drowsiness and
                                                diarrh&#339;a.</hi>&#8212;<name
                                                type="person" key="518">Teamster Edward C.
                                                Ledley</name>, <name type="organization" key="162"
                                                >2d Mich.</name>; age 23; had chills and fever with
                                        diarrh&#339;a <date type="injury" when="1861-08">since the middle of August, 1861</date>, but
                                        attended to his duty as an ambulance driver until <date
                                                type="admit" when="1861-09-06">September 6</date>,
                                        when he was admitted as a case of typhoid fever, presenting
                                        chills, increased local and general heat, anorexia, muscular
                                        debility and pain in the head and bones. On the 11th he was
                                        drowsy and had headache; pulse 78, tongue moist, red at the
                                        tip and brown in the centre, appetite returning. Next
                                        evening the headache continued and he had two stools; but
                                        after this the bowels became regular, the skin moist and
                                        warm, the tongue moist and clean, the pulse natural, the
                                        sleep sound and the appetite and strength improved. He was
                                        returned to duty on <date type="duty" when="1861-09-30"
                                                >the 30th</date>. Dover's powder and turpentine
                                        emulsion, with quinine towards the end, formed the
                                        medication. </p>
                        
